  "response": "Yes, water does exist on Mars, but not in the same form as on Earth. There is evidence of water in several forms:\n\n1. Water ice: \n- Exists in the polar ice caps\n- Present in the form of frost\n- Found in subsurface deposits\n\n2. Liquid water:\n- Likely exists temporarily in some areas, especially during warmer periods\n- Possibly present as briny (salty) liquid water that can remain liquid at lower temperatures\n\n3. Water vapor:\n- Present in the Martian atmosphere, though in very small quantities\n\nWhile liquid water cannot permanently exist on the surface due to low atmospheric pressure and temperature, scientists believe water played a significant role in Mars' geological history and may still exist underground.\n\nNASA's Mars missions, including rovers like Curiosity and Perseverance, continue to study and search for evidence of water and potential signs of past or present microbial life.",
